26 2021-01-03 numbness, pain in extremity I received the shot around 0730 on 12/30/2020. Went home and got ready for work. Around 12am 12/31/2... Read more
Close
I received the shot around 0730 on 12/30/2020. Went home and got ready for work. Around 12am 12/31/2020 my arm started to radiate at the injection site and was very tense. I placed a heat pack on the right harm but the pain did not dissipate. My arm continued to be in pain for the rest of the night. Around 0240 I ate dinner, had water and still had some arm pain. Around 0345 my arm started to flare up and sent pain sensations throughout my body. My right arm was increasingly discomforting, I could barely move it. The sensations spread to my legs, numbing them and my throat had felt as if it were closing up. I got up to get the attention of the nurse and was able to flag her down. She said I was pale as a ghost. My vision was very blurry, I could not hear anything because my ears had filled up and everything was muffled. My head had begun to ring and I was on the brink of fainting when a chair was given to me. My eyes had become extremely sensitive to the light, I was given water and spoken to about what had happened leading up to the event. I was greeted by the paramedics who drew my blood, placed an IV and transferred me to the Acute Care portion of the Emergency Department. My vitals were 76/49, 80/50, 90/56, 100/60 before being brought to the ER. On 1/1/2021 My thighs have been sore/tense, my knees and ankles have been stiff and just feeling sickly. On 1/2/2021 much of the same symptoms are present. The soreness in the muscles isn't as prevalent, however joints still are stiff On 1/3/2021, congestion and runny nose are still present, stiffness in ankles and now shins are prevalent.

26 2021-01-10 cold sweat Initially, around 1500hrs on Monday, January 4th, roughly 40 minutes after the injection, I develope... Read more
Close
Initially, around 1500hrs on Monday, January 4th, roughly 40 minutes after the injection, I developed a scratchy throat, a headache, and nausea. I got home from work, and having no appetite due to nausea, I fell asleep on the couch around 1800hrs. Severe fatigue had set in. I did not wake up until 0500hrs the next morning to go to work on January 5th. I felt like I had not slept at all, however the scratchy throat had gone away. I worked all day with the nausea and headache. Throughout the day I developed chills, cold sweats, diarrhea, fever, and I felt like my mind was foggy (I had felt feverish since Monday night, but Tuesday was the first time I took my temperature that showed I had a fever.) I went home that night and slept all evening and well into the next morning. On the morning of Wednesday, January 6th, my symptoms had again gotten worse, so I called my primary care physician. He fit me in and tested me for the flu and for COVID. He prescribed me Ibuprofen for the headache/fever, and Ondansetron for the nausea/vomiting. My flu test came back negative on Thursday, January 7th, and my COVID test came back negative on Friday, January 8th. The fever finally broke on Friday evening and Saturday, January 9th was the first day I woke up without a fever. I still have the headache as of today, January 11th, and a low grade fever has returned. I am still very fatigued as well.

26 2021-03-18 involuntary muscle movements, grand mal seizure Adverse event reported by nurse . Per RN report, early this morning the patient's mother heard him ... Read more
Close
Adverse event reported by nurse . Per RN report, early this morning the patient's mother heard him call out. When she entered his bedroom she observed "the tail end of a Grand Mal seizure." RN notes that the mother reported symptoms such as stiffness and flailing which was thought to be consistent with a tonic-clonic seizure. Patient was not incontinent, but did experience a period of confusion following the episode, thought be a post-ictal period. EMS was summoned at 8:10am and transported the patient to the emergency department for assessment. RN reports that the patient has no previous history of seizure. Symptoms have resolved and RN reports that the patient has had no recurrent symptoms or seizures while in the emergency department.

Written by Doctor: April 7, 2021 2:09 p.m. DOB 2/07/1995, male, received his second dose of Moderna Vaccine (Lot 019B21A) at 1:13 p.m. He stood up and walked to the usher?s table to have his vaccine card completed. Approximately one minute after receiving his vaccine, he had a syncopal episode falling directly backwards striking his head on the floor. I, MD did not directly witness the fall, but everyone who witnessed the fall said that he fell completely unimpeded to the floor. I was notified and immediately assisted the patient who was with his girlfriend. Patient initially appeared ?out?, but almost immediately opened his eyes and asked what happened. His skin was cool and clammy. A pulse oximeter was placed on his finger registering 98% o2 and a pulse of 53. I kept him lying on the floor until he was completely awake and aware of his surroundings. At the time he said his neck was not sore, but his head was sore. Approximately 2-3 minutes later, we were able to assist him in standing to immediately sit down in a wheelchair. He was taken to the cot in the hallway just outside the Medical Observation where I was able to help him to stand and then lie down. An icepack was provided to put on the back of his head, he was provided water, Gatorade, and two cookies. Patient said that he hadn?t eaten all day and had been feeling slightly hungry prior to his vaccination. I had patient move all extremities and asked his questions to verify that he was full awake and oriented to person, place, and time. Patient girlfriend stayed with patient while he ate his cookies. I addressed my concerns about patient striking his head on the floor and the possibility of a closed head injury. Girlfriend felt that patient was now completely back to his normal state of mind. I had patient remain lying down for 20 minutes. When I returned to check on him, he was sitting up and wanted to leave. I told him that he needed to be able to walk up and down the hallway before I would feel comfortable letting him leave. He stood up and walked halfway down the hallway before saying he was lightheaded. I immediately went to him to lead him back to the cot, but he insisted that he needed to use the bathroom to urinate. Both girlfriend and I stood in the doorway to assist patient if he needed, but he was able to finish urinating, then returned and sat in the wheelchair. I spoke to both Doctors via a phone call and had spoken to someone earlier. After letting them know that patient did not want an ambulance called, but I was going to strongly recommend he go to the nearest ER before returning home, I returned to the patient. Vital signs at 1:53 were Pulse Ox of 98%, pulse 78, and blood pressure sitting of 140/75. Again, I strongly recommended that girlfriend drive him to an ED for an evaluation and possible cat scan. Patient also now had some paracervical neck pain which I also said should be evaluated. Patient and girlfriend both insisted they didn?t want an ambulance called and girlfriend felt comfortable taking patient out of the clinic. Patient said he was hungry, and they were going to get food first. Girlfriend gave me her phone number (xxx)xxx-xxxx and I gave her my phone number (xxx-xxx-xxxx). I told her I was going to call her every hour to check on patient and told her to call me at any time. I recommended acetaminophen for the headache and other vaccine symptoms but no ibuprofen because of the possible head injury. I recommended to immediately call an ambulance or go to an ED for nausea, worsening headache, confusion, or drowsiness. Girlfriend is not to let patient sleep longer than 30 minutes at a time. Patient was able to walk out of the clinic easily under his own power without any assistance. He stated he was feeling much better.

27 2021-04-27 one side paralysis, muscle twitching, numbness, seizure like phenomena Moderna Covid-19 Vaccine 03/11/2021 received first dose of Moderna. By next day, expected flu-like s... Read more
Close
Moderna Covid-19 Vaccine 03/11/2021 received first dose of Moderna. By next day, expected flu-like symptoms were apparent such as chills, headache, and body aches. Then, full body muscle twitches and motor tics began. The continue six weeks later. On the 7th day post-vaccine, early AM sleep paralysis/seizure sensation 4-5 times before falling back asleep. When awoken, unilateral weakness (right side). Right eye vision blurry. Right ear muffled. Subjective weakness and numbness in right arm and leg. Went to ER and was admitted under suspicion of TIA or mild stroke. CT w/oC appeared unremarkable. Scheduled for a brain MRI following day (3/19) WWO contrast. Appeared unremarkable, so acute ischaemia was ruled out. Blood work was done repeatedly during stay (CBC, metabolic, CRP, sed rate, urinalysis). Everything was unremarkable. Discharged with instruction to follow-up if symptoms did not improve. The unilateral weakness is intermittent six weeks later. On 4/20, allergist tested against components of Moderna vaccine intradermally. This showed a reaction compared to the negative control. Allergist advised to avoid further vaccination with any of the ingredients in Moderna. Allergist posited that symptoms could be a latent reaction to the allergy, but wasn't sure as prolonged presentation seems unlikely. Future follow-ups: rheumatologist to rule out acute autoimmune reaction, 4/21/21. Neurologist second opinion 5/4/21. Primary care evaluation, as PCP was on leave for several months, 5/19/21.

27 2021-05-19 cold sweat Starting at about 5pm on the day of vaccination, I experienced intense but expected side effects inc... Read more
Close
Starting at about 5pm on the day of vaccination, I experienced intense but expected side effects including full body muscle ache, fever, drowsiness, cold sweats, joint pain. These symptoms lasted for about 24hrs before subsiding completely by that Tuesday evening. On Thursday, 5/13, I woke up with moderate tightness in my chest that progressed over the course of 45 minutes to be severe chest pain. At that point, my wife drove me to the ER in where I was checked in at about 8:30am. By the time I was checked in the chest pain had subsided to be just a slight discomfort, overall the chest pain had lasted for approximately 2 hours. At the ER my bloodwork was done and the initial blood samples returned an elevated Troponin I level of 5.04 ng/ml. While at the ER at the I experienced one more incident of chest pain which lasted roughly 30 minutes and was moderately low on the pain scale. I was given multiple EKGs, X-rays, and Echocardiograms, all of which showed no abnormalities. Repeated troponin tests however showed an increase in my levels over the course of the day from 5 up to 12.6 and 13. I was placed on a heparin drip in the afternoon. By doctor recommendation I was air-lifted to later that night at 10:30pm so that further scans and a possible cardiac catheterization and CT scans. The following day, Friday, at 1am at my bloodwork was taken and troponin levels had increased to 14. I was scheduled for a CT scan, cardiac MRI, and echocardiogram to confirm the diagnosis of Myocarditis. By Saturday afternoon I was taken off of the heparin drip and told that they would not be able to perform any of the scheduled tests until Monday at the earliest. My most recent troponin level came back as a 9. At this point I decided to check myself out of against medical advice since they were not able to run the necessary scans and my wife and I do not live in . I returned home to and followed up on 5/19 with a doctor at the ER at since I was unable to find any available appointments with any cardiologists in the area for the next few weeks. My troponin levels and EKG taken at came back as normal, so I continue to follow doctor advice of bedrest and no alcohol for the next 4-6 weeks. My pulse is still elevated (roughly 85 bpm resting when it used to be at <65 bpm resting) and seems to easily increase with even moderate activity such as walking in the house up to over 100 bpm.

28 2021-05-27 seizure like phenomena After administration, the patient sat in a chair for observation. 2-3 minutes after administration ... Read more
Close
After administration, the patient sat in a chair for observation. 2-3 minutes after administration patient had a loss of consciousness, falling out of his chair onto the carpeted floor. Patient observed having seizure-like contractions of his upper extremities and slight arching of his back while having this loss of consciousness. LOC lasted less than 10 seconds. Patient was placed on his side, and when he regained consciousness could answer all questions appropriately and without delay. Patient was placed in a wheel chair and taken to a private observation area where vital signs could be attained. Patient again had a LOC while being wheeled in the wheel chair to the private observation area. Patient was placed on a gurney, supine. Vital signs taken and patient was found to have a heart rate in the 40s and a blood pressure of 90/66. Patient was ashen and diaphoretic. Patient was observed for 30 minutes in the private observation area where his condition improved to normal before leaving the facility.

28 2021-06-03 tingling, discomfort Just after midnight, I was watching TV with my brother after smoking a medical pre-roll (I'm a medic... Read more
Close
Just after midnight, I was watching TV with my brother after smoking a medical pre-roll (I'm a medical marijuana patient). Shortly after, I began feeling dizzy. I finished my glass of water and the dizziness subsided for roughly ten minutes, before returning even worse than before. I went to get more water and after filling my glass and closing the refrigerator, I was barely able to walk the few steps from my kitchen to the living room to lie down on the couch. At this time, my chest started feeling tight, and I had a light tingling sensation in my feet and lower body. When I closed my eyes, the dizziness got worse, and laying in certain positions made the tightness in my upper chest become painful. I continued to drink water and ate a little, but the episode lasted between 30-60 minutes of mild discomfort ranging to a decent amount of pain. There was a moment when I had considered going to the hospital, but after eating, drinking, and doing some controlled breathing, the pain lessened I ended up falling asleep on the couch. I woke up feeling considerably better, but decided to call out of work so I wouldn't do any strenuous activity. On occassion I still feel like there's a little bit of pressure or tightness in my upper chest, but nothing painful or debilitating like the night of the incident

Fainted 3 times/can't stay more than 30 to 45 seconds; Need to lay on the floor/not stay for more than 30-45 seconds; Need to lay on the floor; Injection site pain; Chills; Fever; Body aches/muscle aches; Swollen lymph nodes; sore arm; This spontaneous case was reported by a consumer and describes the occurrence of SYNCOPE (Fainted 3 times/can't stay more than 30 to 45 seconds), LETHARGY (Need to lay on the floor/not stay for more than 30-45 seconds), FATIGUE (Need to lay on the floor), VACCINATION SITE PAIN (Injection site pain), CHILLS (Chills), PYREXIA (Fever), MYALGIA (Body aches/muscle aches), LYMPHADENOPATHY (Swollen lymph nodes) and PAIN IN EXTREMITY (sore arm) in a 29-year-old male patient who received mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (batch nos. 003C21A and 037B21A) for COVID-19 vaccination. Concurrent medical conditions included Seasonal allergy. Concomitant products included CETIRIZINE HYDROCHLORIDE (ZYRTEC [CETIRIZINE HYDROCHLORIDE]) for Seasonal allergy. On 22-Apr-2021, the patient received first dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) 1 dosage form. On 27-May-2021 at 5:00 PM, received second dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) dosage was changed to 1 dosage form. On 28-May-2021, the patient experienced SYNCOPE (Fainted 3 times/can't stay more than 30 to 45 seconds) (seriousness criteria disability and medically significant), FATIGUE (Need to lay on the floor) (seriousness criterion disability), VACCINATION SITE PAIN (Injection site pain) (seriousness criterion disability), CHILLS (Chills) (seriousness criterion disability), PYREXIA (Fever) (seriousness criterion disability), MYALGIA (Body aches/muscle aches) (seriousness criterion disability), LYMPHADENOPATHY (Swollen lymph nodes) (seriousness criterion disability) and PAIN IN EXTREMITY (sore arm) (seriousness criterion disability). 28-May-2021, the patient experienced LETHARGY (Need to lay on the floor/not stay for more than 30-45 seconds) (seriousness criterion disability). The patient was treated with DEXTROMETHORPHAN HYDROBROMIDE, DOXYLAMINE SUCCINATE, EPHEDRINE SULFATE, ETHANOL, PARACETAMOL (NYQUIL) for Fever, at a dose of 0.5 dosage form. At the time of the report, SYNCOPE (Fainted 3 times/can't stay more than 30 to 45 seconds), LETHARGY (Need to lay on the floor/not stay for more than 30-45 seconds), FATIGUE (Need to lay on the floor), VACCINATION SITE PAIN (Injection site pain), CHILLS (Chills), PYREXIA (Fever), MYALGIA (Body aches/muscle aches), LYMPHADENOPATHY (Swollen lymph nodes) and PAIN IN EXTREMITY (sore arm) outcome was unknown. Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events was not applicable. Based on the current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the events, a causal relationship cannot be excluded. This case was linked to MOD-2021-186579 (Patient Link).; Sender's Comments: Based on the current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the events, a causal relationship cannot be excluded.
29 2021-06-03 tenderness, pain in extremity The first day after I received the vaccine I experienced symptoms in guidance with all available res... Read more
Close
The first day after I received the vaccine I experienced symptoms in guidance with all available resources. I was fatigued, my arm was sore at the sight of injection. I remember sleeping at least 12 hours. A few days later I began to experience severe intermittent chest pain. The area under my arm was extremely tender, as were the area behind my left knee. The adverse event as stated in the report was a sudden jolt of searing pain on my left side. It lasted only a few moments and felt like it traveled from my left shoulder down to my left thigh and behind my knee. It nearly knocked me off my feet. I remained with a lingering pain in my leg and upper left back until today. I reached out the pharmacist who administered the vaccine about the side effects and she advised me to immediately contact my doctor's office. I visited my doctor's office yesterday (6/3/21) and he assured me I didn't have any blood clots. He advised me to use a heating pad for the pain in my leg. He also said that sometimes the lingering side effects from the vaccine may last weeks in rare cases. Those discomforts are finally starting to subside. I had no treatment outside of elevated levels of hydration, taking Tylenol and resting.

30 2021-02-23 night sweats Fever of 101 degrees F that is on and off/100.7 F; Wasn't not able to swallow or eat at all; Severe ... Read more
Close
Fever of 101 degrees F that is on and off/100.7 F; Wasn't not able to swallow or eat at all; Severe red sore throat with white points; Very sweaty especially at night; a little bit of delirious; Severe chills where his teeth were chattering; Sore throat/In agony with a sore throat; Sore arm; When he first got the vaccine he said "Boy you can really feel something going on in there"; A spontaneous report was received from a consumer regarding her son, a 30-year-old male patient who received Moderna's COVID-19 vaccine (mRNA-1273) and experienced a little bit delirious/delirious, sore throat, sore arm/vaccination site pain, chills, fever/pyrexia, when first receiving the vaccine he stated "boy you can really feel something going on in there"/ vaccination site dysathesia, swallowing difficult/dysphagia, severe red sore throat with white points/throat infection, and very sweaty at night/night sweats. The patient's medical history was not included. Products known to have been used by the patient were Vitamin D3, Creatine monohydrate and Fish Oil. On 11 January 2021, prior to the onset of the events, the patient received the first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Lot number: 025L20A) intramuscularly in the left deltoid for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection. On 12 January 2021, the patient reported a sore throat, and sore arm, took 2 ibuprofen, which patient reported as helped. On 14 January 2021, the patient reported chills, sore throat in agony with sore throat, and fever. Patient took ibuprofen, which he reported as helping and was able to sleep. The soreness in the arm was reported as gone. On 17 January 2021, the patient's mother reported he was still having fever and was a little bit delirious. 31 2021-03-04 pain in extremity At approximately 930 am, Offender was vaccinated in Housing Unit and returned to his bed. He was mon... Read more
Close
At approximately 930 am, Offender was vaccinated in Housing Unit and returned to his bed. He was monitored by nursing staff for 15 minutes and had no adverse reaction or side effects. At approximately 1030am, Offender was called to the officer's desk and was told to report to the visiting room for vaccination. Upon arrival, offender was again vaccinated in the opposite arm. Offender was called in error rather than his room mate was who was an add on to the vaccination list. Offender was admitted to the Health Care Unit for observation for 24 hrs. Vital signs remained stable throughout this period with only a complaint of bilateral sore arms. There were nono additional sequelae. Office of Health Services was notified of the incident on February 25, 2021 and began a review as part of our quality improvement process and in order to recommend practice modifications, provide education, implement policy change, monitor outcomes and prevent re-occurrence. OHS reviewed information obtained from Moderna regarding the management of vaccine administration errors. The error at facility is known as an "invalid dose". In general there is limited information, yet low risk, for individuals who either receive a second dose within 21 days or a higher than authorized dose volume. The recommendations in this guidance related to the facility occurrence are summarized: Second dose administered in < 21 days Do not repeat dose. Higher than authorized dose volume administered Do not repeat dose. *  Inform the recipient of the potential for local and systemic adverse. Additional recommendations from the process: 1. Identity verification. There were several opportunities for Health Care Staff, Security Staff, and Guardsmen to confirm the identify of Offender. a. All offenders must wear their ID throughout all steps of the vaccination process. b. Health Care Staff, Security Staff, andGuardsmen must verify offender identities as needed for their assignments throughout each step the vaccination process c. Health care staff must verify accurate completion of offender vaccination forms and ensure that forms match the offender being vaccinated. d. Health care and Security staff must identify offenders by offender name and number rather than housing assignment. e. Use of handwritten lists should be minimized. Other pre-printed available rosters or spreadsheets are preferable 2. Offender completed two sets of consent forms for vaccination. It is unclear if he did not understand the process, or exactly why he would repeat the vaccination process. a. Though language did not appear to be an issue, appropriate interpreters should be made available to obtain consents and provide education. b. When necessary consent forms should be provided in the native language spoken by the offender. c. It is unclear why there was no further attempt to confirm that Offender had previously received a vaccination that day, after stating that fact to those present before he received his second dose of vaccine. In the future, if an individual states that he or she has already been vaccinated the process must stop until his or her claims have been verified or shown to be false. 3. Any unplanned changes to the onsite vaccination plan (add-ons, extra dose redistribution, team deployment etc.) must be communicated to all members of the vaccination team. 4. Health care staff alone are responsible for the completion of all consent forms and vaccination documentation. 5. Identify best practices and standardize vaccination add-ons across facilities. Consider: location, addition to master vaccination roster, etc. a. Perhaps add-on vaccinations can be moved to another area for tracking. b. Add-ons should be added to the master vaccination roster. Additional recommendations: 6. Re-Training on the vaccination protocol for health care, operations and national guard staff. The above items were completed.

My blood %SpO2 read between 95 and 98% and pulse ranged from 95 to 101 bpm. I did NOT experience: difficulty breathing, swelling of the airway, nor itching. Since I was not having difficulty breathing, and my symptoms seemed to indicate low blood pressure or potentially low blood sugar I decided to wait it out and see if my symptoms worsened. While laying on the floor, I consumed a glass of milk and a few oreo cookies, hoping to counter hypoglycemia (if that's what was going on). After approximately 15 minutes my condition began to improve - I could sit up slightly with only mild dizziness and color began returning to my face. After approximately 30 minutes, I was able to stand and walk to my couch and lay down. After around an hour, I was feeling almost back to normal with only a slight dizziness and tiredness remaining. 12 hours after the adverse event (24 hours post vaccination) I feel okay, slightly lightheaded but generally fine. I intend to call a doctor and discuss if any further tests are necessary.

grand maul seizure; vision changes; Feelings of pressure at the back of his neck radiating to right side of his head; This spontaneous case was reported by a physician (subsequently medically confirmed) and describes the occurrence of GENERALISED TONIC-CLONIC SEIZURE (grand maul seizure) in an adult male patient who received mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) for COVID-19 vaccination. The occurrence of additional non-serious events is detailed below. Co-suspect product included non-company product ADALIMUMAB (HUMIRA) solution for injection for Crohn's disease. Concurrent medical conditions included Crohn's disease (moderate to severe). On 14-Oct-2020, the patient started ADALIMUMAB (HUMIRA) (Subcutaneous) dosage form. On an unknown date, the patient received first dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) 1 dosage form. On an unknown date, the patient experienced GENERALISED TONIC-CLONIC SEIZURE (grand maul seizure) (seriousness criterion hospitalization), VISUAL IMPAIRMENT (vision changes) and NECK PAIN (Feelings of pressure at the back of his neck radiating to right side of his head). At the time of the report, GENERALISED TONIC-CLONIC SEIZURE (grand maul seizure) had resolved and VISUAL IMPAIRMENT (vision changes) and NECK PAIN (Feelings of pressure at the back of his neck radiating to right side of his head) outcome was unknown. The action taken with mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) was unknown. For mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular), the reporter did not provide any causality assessments. The patient had a seizure three days after his first Moderna Covid vaccine and was hospitalized. CT scan was negative. The reporter's causality for co-suspect drug, adalimumab, was not provided. Concomitant product use was not provided. No treatment information was provided. This case concerns an adult male, with PMH of Crohn's disease, hospitalized with a serious unexpected event of generalized tonic-clonic seizure (grand mal seizure), and nonserious unexpected visual impairment and neck pain. Event onset with unknown latency after first dose mRNA-1273. They kept me overnight and after taking more blood tests and ECG tests were able to diagnose me with Pericarditis on Saturday morning. I was prescribed colchicine, which I am to take twice a day for three months and ibuprofen to manage the pain.

Close
After the individual received his vaccine he went to the medical monitoring area with two additional members of his party. At approximately 1412 the individuals friends alerted me that he needs help. I walked approximately 40 feet to find a 33 year old male patient that was unconscious and seizing. The seizure lasted about 20-30 seconds with the patient waking up confused. I instructed someone from my team to call 911 and request an ambulance. Another team member and myself assisted the patient to a wheelchair and moved him to our treatment area approximately 50 feet away. The patient was somewhat confused, hot & sweaty and fatigued. I took a basic set of vital signs and got: BP 90/70 Pulse 56 Respirations 22 LOC x 4 No CBG The ambulance arrived within 10 minuets and another round of vitals were taken. The patients blood pressure and pulse were still low. A CBG of 120 was achieved. The patient was still hot / sweaty and fatigued. The patient lied down on a cot and soon started feeling better. He stopped sweating and his BP / Pulse started rising to within normal limits. The two paramedics on site conducted a 12 lead ECG and didn't notice any amoralities. Due to this incident being the first of its kind for the patient and without being a able to find a definitive known cause it was recommended that the patient be transported to the local hospital for further evaluation. The patient declined and stated that he would have his friends take him if he starting feeling really bad. It was strongly advised that he be transported via medics to the hospital but in the end the patient refused.

Fainted; Disoriented and didn't know what was happening; Feels a little dizzy; Lethargy; Tenderness in the arm; A spontaneous report was received from a consumer who was a 36-year-old, male, patient, who received Moderna's COVID-19 Vaccine (mRNA-1273) and experienced fainted, tenderness in the arm, lethargy, disoriented and didn't know what was happening, and feels a little dizzy. The patient's medical history was not provided. No relevant concomitant medications were reported. On 14 Jan 2021, prior to the onset of events, the patient received the first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Lot number: 25L20A) intramuscularly in the left arm for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection. On the evening of 14 Jan 2021, the patient had tenderness in the arm and felt lethargic. On 15 Jan 2021, the patient fainted when he woke up in the morning. The patient's legs gave out and he fell into the wall. The patient was disoriented and didn't know what was happening. The patient reported the event as happening pretty quick and described it as "like he had very low blood sugar". The patient reported that sometimes when he gets up too quickly, he feels a little dizzy. No treatment information was provided. Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events was not reported. The outcome of the events, fainted, tenderness in the arm, lethargy, disoriented and didn't know what was happening, and sometimes when he gets up too quickly, was unknown. The event, feels a little dizzy, was considered not resolved.; Reporter's Comments: This spontaneous report refers to a case of a 36-year-old male patient who experienced events of fainted, tenderness in the arm, lethargy, disoriented and didn't know what was happening, and feels a little dizzy. The events developed on the following day after the administration of the mRNA-1273 vaccine (Lot # 25L20A, expiration date-unknown). No treatment was reported, and outcome is resolved for dizziness and unknown for all other events. Based on the information provided which includes a temporal association, a causal association cannot be excluded

Patient stated in general he was not feeling any better and feeling slightly worse BP was again noted to be 220/110. When I woke up today on 5/11, the burning-numbing sensation returned to my arm again (even as I type this) but this time I know it is not a stroke. I have had no medical history, exercise regularly, have a healthy diet (vegetarian/vegan for more than seven years), the only thing I've done recently is had my first Moderna shot injected intramuscularly in my left arm, the same arm where this burning-numbness is taking place. 38 2021-03-15 nerve pain Approximately 12 hours after my second Moderna vaccine, I experienced the typical body aches, chills... Read more
Close
Approximately 12 hours after my second Moderna vaccine, I experienced the typical body aches, chills, headache, and tiredness expected in someone my age (38). I was initially happy that my immune system seemed to have a positive response to the second dose. About 24 hours after my second dose, I developed a severe headache and nerve pain all over the right side of my head. No over the counter medicine would relieve the pain. The next day, I developed a rash on my forehead. The rash quickly spread and consumed the right side of my face and my right eye. I was seen by medical staff, and received a diagnosis of severe shingles. I was given Valtrex and, eventually, gabapentin. My eye continued to get worse and I lost clear vision in my right eye. I saw an ophthalmologist and was told that the shingles had activated in the eye. My eye pressure was dangerously high. I was given steroid drops and drops to relieve eye pressure. Since February 22, I have battled shingles. My rash is gone and my eye has cleared. But, I still suffer from intense nerve pain in my head, forehead, and eye. All medical professionals opined that the moderna vaccine must have played a role given the timing. If shingles can be considered a side effect, it is one that has been intense and long-lasting.

38 2021-05-03 feeling of insects crawling on skin, tremor, tingling, pain in extremity, muscle twitching, feeling cold, weakness On Friday, April 2nd, I received my first dose of the Moderna vaccine. Within minutes, my heart sta... Read more
Close
On Friday, April 2nd, I received my first dose of the Moderna vaccine. Within minutes, my heart started racing and I felt faint. Thereafter, my hands and face got the sensation of tingling. It felt like ice was running through my veins. My heart stopped racing approximately fifteen or so minutes after it began. The tingling sensation in my hands and face ended approximately one hour later. I also noticed a strange taste in my mouth during this same timeframe. Subsequently, I had the sensation of being dizzy and lightheaded. Importantly, I have never reacted to a vaccine in this manner. On Saturday, April 3rd, I woke up with symptoms that were to be expected. My arm was very sore and I felt a little achy. However, I continued to feel dizzy and lightheaded. That evening and for the next week or so, my heart was beating rapidly, and my blood pressure was elevated. I also had the continuous feeling of my skin crawling. My hands and feet also seemed to be experiencing tremors and twitching. On Sunday, April 4th, I woke up and noticed that my right eye seemed a little blurry as I read an article on my phone. I assumed I must have slept on my eye wrong and did not pay it much attention. I do not recall my eye being blurry for the rest of the day. The following morning on Monday, April 5th, I woke up once again feeling dizzy and lightheaded. As I walked to the restroom, I noticed that my right eye was blurry again. This time it seemed to be more pronounced. Moreover, when I closed my right eye, I could see hundreds of dots in different colors. In addition to having blurry vision, my legs felt weak and nearly buckled as I walked. I felt like I was intoxicated. Upon returning to bed, my teeth began chattering and I felt like I was freezing. I called my doctor?s office and spoke with a PA who recommended that I go to the ER. While I checked in at the ER, I could not remember my ZIP code. I felt like my brain was not running on all cylinders. Upon explaining my symptomology to the ER doctor, she recommended that I have my blood drawn and that I get an MRI to rule out a stroke. All test results came back normal. On Wednesday, April 7th, I made an appointment with an allergist. They tested me to see if I was allergic to Polyethylene Glycol (PEG) and Polysorbate 80. For the skin scratch portion of the test, neither of the substances had much of a reaction on my skin. I thought the Polysorbate 80 scratch had a little bit of redness to it, but it was negligible. When the doctor injected Polysorbate 80 under my skin with a syringe, a welt formed. I am not sure why, but PEG was not injected in the same manner. As a result of the test, the allergist confirmed that I am allergic to Polysorbate 80. He mentioned that there may be instances of cross reactivity to PEG for individuals that are allergic to Polysorbate 80. He recommended that I not get the second Moderna dose unless it was administered in a controlled setting. On Sunday April 11th, I noticed what felt like a hard vein in my abdominal fat. It felt slightly tender to the touch. I was fearful that it could be a clot. On Tuesday, April 13th, I woke up and as a I stood in the shower, my foot was painful to stand on. On top of my right foot near my ankle, I could visibly see red inflammation in a vein. I massaged the vein and the redness and pain dissipated. Being fearful that I did have blood clots, I scheduled an appointment with a PA at my doctor?s office that same day. We discussed my ongoing dizziness, lightheadedness, and me being fearful of blood clots. She had an EKG performed at the office and ordered a barrage of blood tests. Everything continued to be normal. On Sunday, April 18th, I again went to the ER, because the hard vein in my stomach became larger and more tender to the touch. When I bent over, it felt like there was a lot of pressure emanating from the hard vein down to my groin. Once again, blood was drawn and everything was normal. I also had an ultrasound performed on the area that felt like a hard vein and the doctor concluded that it was most likely swollen lymph nodes. I was diagnosed with lymphadenopathy. On Monday, April 26th, I scheduled an appointment with my primary care doctor to discuss the ongoing dizziness, lightheadedness, and pain in my stomach and groin area. He told me that he had seen other patients that were experiencing similar symptoms and that my immune system was possibly overreacting to the vaccine. He told me the symptoms should go away in time. He also ordered a new blood test to check for clots. The D-Dimer test came back normal. On Tuesday, April 27th, I experienced a painful genital herpes outbreak. I normally get one every year. I had just recovered from an infection in December of 2020. This outbreak was more intense and for the first time I had nerve pain that wrapped around my hip and down my inner thigh. As of a week later, the infection is almost gone. Today is May 4th, and I am still experiencing dizziness and lightheadedness. Some days are better than others and every time I get optimistic that my dizziness and lightheadedness is finally gone, it reappears. Being an IT consultant business owner and an attorney, I need to think clearly for my profession. The side effects from the Moderna vaccine have made it very difficult to function. I would like to get fully vaccinated, but I am fearful of getting the second shot. I do not want the vaccine to cause permanent neurological damage or worse. Finally, I am sure your organization is aware, but there are many other people experiencing the same symptoms as me.

1 week after the second dose, I was exercising in the early morning when suddenly my vision and hand-eye coordination were flashing, my hand appeared in a different position than where I thought it was. I tried to tell my sons to get help, but I couldn't say any words, just some repetitive mumbling. I was able to walk upstairs but couldn't speak for about 10 mins, and then everything was coming out slowly. It was about an hour before I could resume normal talking. I went to the hospital, where they gave me a CT scan, MRI, heart echo, and eventually a TEE. They said that I had a Transient Ischemic Attack, and they found a PFO in my heart that probably allowed a blood clot to travel to my brain. They also did an ultrasound of my legs when I mentioned the timing of the vaccine, to make sure there were no other clots. I am taking baby asprin and crestor, and have an heart event monitor now for 30 days. I am also scheduled for more bloodwork and a pelvic scan. They say it is likely that they will want to close my PFO, but want to see all the test results first to rule out any other possible causes.

Patient has no clotting history. He developed body aches, left arm pain, and fevers immediately after immunization, but improved. Two days later on 6/2, he developed left flank pain and fevers. On 6/4, he was evaluated in the ED, with CT scan showing partially occlusive thrombosis of left renal artery with areas of renal infarction. Cr remained stably at baseline. Initial workup was otherwise notable for WBC 17 and negative infectious workup. He was initiated on therapeutic Lovenox. On 6/5, CTA chest/abdomen/pelvis was performed to evaluate for other clots. Left renal artery was complete thromboses with evolving foci of renal infarction. No other clots were detected. He continued to have fevers. By 6/8, his leukocytosis, fever, and flank pain resolved. His coagulability workup was notable for positive LAC, FVII deficiency, and PET/CT without evidence of occult malignancy.
